-- Heating Oil Leads Drop as Carbon Tumbles: Commodities at Close
-- B y   C l a u d i a   C a r p e n t e r
-- 2013-04-16T15:35:32Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2013-04-16/heating-oil-leads-drop-as-carbon-tumbles-commodities-at-close.html
The Standard & Poor’s GSCI gauge of
24 commodities fell 0.5 percent to 605.61 by 4:32 p.m. in
 London . The UBS Bloomberg CMCI  index  of 26 raw materials was up
0.3 percent at 1,462.162.  OIL PRODUCTS  Ultra-low sulfur diesel slid to a nine-month low as Brent
crude and gasoil slipped amid declining fuel demand in Europe.
Heating oil dropped 1.8 percent, the fifth consecutive decline.  Ultra-low-sulfur diesel for May delivery declined 2.94
cents to $2.7998 a gallon on the New York Mercantile Exchange on
volume that was 7.7 percent below the 100-day average. Prices
touched $2.7712, the lowest intraday level since July 13.  Gasoil in Europe for May delivery on the ICE Futures Europe
exchange fell 0.7 percent to $841 a metric ton. Brent for June
settlement fell $1.08 to $99.55 a barrel.  Gasoline for May delivery sank 2.01 cents, or 0.7 percent,
to $2.7375 a gallon on volume that was 20 percent above the 100-
day average. Prices touched $2.7036, the lowest intraday level
in three months.  Gasoline at the pump, averaged nationwide, fell 0.4 cent to
$3.522 a gallon, AAA said today on its website. Prices have
fallen 26.4 cents from the year-to-date high of $3.786 on Feb.
26 and are 38.5 cents below a year ago.  Oil Products  Europe : NI OPEMKT Gasoline: NI GASOLINE Heating
oil: NI HEATOIL  European Carbon Permits  European Union emission permits tumbled 34 percent to 3.16
euros a metric ton after the European Parliament rejected a
proposed change to Europe’s emissions-trading law that would
allow the supply of carbon permits to be curbed temporarily.  EU Carbon Emissions: NI ECBMKT  SOFT COMMODITIES  Sugar rebounded in New York on speculation prices fell too
far as commodities slid to the lowest level in nine months.
Cocoa jumped 2 percent.  Raw sugar for July delivery advanced 1 percent to 17.73
cents a pound on ICE Futures U.S. in New York. The futures for
May were up 0.7 percent to 17.92 cents a pound.  Arabica-coffee futures for delivery in July rose 0.7
percent to $1.371 a pound on ICE. Robusta-coffee futures for
delivery in July rose 0.7 percent to $2,072 a ton on NYSE Liffe.  Soft commodities markets: NI SOMKTS  PRECIOUS METALS  Gold rebounded as some investors deemed a 13 percent plunge
over two days to be excessive and an Asian central banker said
that policy makers may take the opportunity to buy. Silver also
advanced.  Gold futures for June delivery gained 1.5 percent to
$1,381.60 an ounce at 9:59 a.m. on the Comex in New York,
heading for the biggest gain for a most-active contract since
April 5. Prices earlier touched $1,321.50, the lowest since Jan.
28, 2011. Yesterday’s 9.3 percent tumble was the biggest since
1980.  Silver futures for May delivery jumped 0.4 percent to
$23.455 ounce on the Comex. Earlier, prices touched $22, the
lowest since Oct. 5, 2010. Yesterday, the precious metal
retreated 11 percent, the biggest drop since Sept. 23, 2011.  Precious metal markets: NI PCMKTS  BASE METALS  Copper rose in London after a plunge to the lowest level in
almost 18 months encouraged buyers in  China , the world’s biggest
consumer of the metal. Aluminum jumped 2.1 percent.  Copper for delivery in three months climbed 0.8 percent to
$7,258 a metric ton on the London Metal Exchange. Prices
yesterday touched $7,085, the lowest since Oct. 21, 2011. Copper
for delivery in May added 0.1 percent to $3.2765 a pound on the
Comex in New York.  Base metals markets: NI BMMKTS  NATURAL GAS  Natural gas futures fluctuated in New York amid speculation
that a shot of cold weather in the central U.S. will spur fuel
usage.  Natural gas for May delivery rose 0.3 cent to $4.14 per
million British thermal units at 9:36 a.m. on the New York
Mercantile Exchange. Trading was 47 percent above the 100-day
average for the time of day.  U.K. natural gas: NI NUKMKT Gas market: NI GASMARKET Americas
natural gas: NI AGASMARKET European natural gas: NI EGASMARKET  GRAINS, OILSEEDS  Soybeans rebounded in  Chicago  on speculation demand will
increase after prices slumped to the lowest level in almost 10
months.  Soybeans for delivery in July gained 0.7 percent to
$13.6525 a bushel at 7:18 a.m. on the Chicago Board of Trade,
after tumbling 1.7 percent yesterday.  Corn for delivery in July was little changed at $6.275 a
bushel, after declining 2.1 percent yesterday.  Wheat futures for delivery in July rose 0.5 percent to
$7.025 a bushel. In Paris, milling wheat for delivery in
November gained 0.4 percent.  Grains markets: NI GRMKTS  LIVESTOCK  Hog futures for June settlement rose 0.6 percent to 89.1
cents a pound on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange.  Cattle futures for June delivery gained 0.5 percent to
$1.204 a pound on the CME.  Feeder-cattle futures for August settlement rose 0.1
percent to $1.4655 a pound.  Livestock markets: NI LVMKTS  CRUDE OIL  Brent crude dropped below $100 a barrel for the first time
since July on signs global economic growth will slow, curbing
fuel use. West Texas Intermediate oil slipped to a four-month
low on speculation U.S. stockpiles rose.  Brent oil for June settlement fell $1.46, or 1.5 percent,
to $99.17 on the London-based ICE Futures Europe exchange at
10:55 a.m. New York time. The May futures contract expired at
$100.39 yesterday. The volume of all futures traded was more
than double the 100-day average for the time of day.  WTI crude for May delivery slipped 73 cents, or 0.8
percent, to $87.98 a barrel on the New York Mercantile Exchange.
Prices fell as much as $2.65 to $86.06 earlier. The volume of
all futures traded was 97 percent above the 100-day average.  Oil markets: NI OILMARKET  To contact the reporter on this story:
